abstract = {In last two decades use of wireless sensor network (WSN) technology has significantly increases precision of the agricultural systems. This fulfills the requirement of the higher productivity. WSNs are proving a dominant technology for collecting and processing the agricultural data at low cost and also minimize the overall energy consumption. The productivity of the agriculture highly depends open the nature of the soil. Thus, first part of this paper is aimed to review the work done for measuring the soil parameters using various hardware and second part various energy efficient protocols used for minimizing the energy of the WSN are reviewed. The basic structure of the WSN system as a combination of hardware and software for automatically controlling and monitoring the soil parameters are described along with block diagram. Under the hardware part sensors node units were described using temperature, humidity and pH sensors, while in software part the energy efficient protocol are proposed to design. Paper also presents the comparison of the range cost and complexity of the various available WSN techniques. Various challenges and limitations of the existing energy minimization approaches are formulated as problems. Finally it is concluded that it is highly required to improve the energy efficiency of the long range WSN for soil parameter monitoring}
